  "prompt": "How much does IVF increase a woman's odds of having twins or multiple babies at once?",
  "response": "In vitro fertilization (IVF) significantly increases the likelihood of having twins or multiple babies compared to natural conception. This is primarily due to the practice of transferring multiple embryos during the procedure to improve the chances of a successful pregnancy. Here\u2019s an overview of the probabilities:\n\n1. **Natural Conception**: The chance of having twins naturally is about 1 in 250 (0.4%), while the chance of having triplets or more is extremely rare (less than 0.1%).\n\n2. **IVF with Multiple Embryo Transfer**: With IVF, the odds of having twins or multiples depend on the number of embryos transferred:\n   - **Twins**: The likelihood of twins with IVF is around 20-30% if two embryos are transferred.\n   - **Triplets or More**: The chances are lower, around 3-5%, but still much higher than with natural conception.\n\n3. **Single Embryo Transfer (SET)**: To reduce the risk of multiples, many clinics now recommend transferring just one embryo, especially in younger patients or those with good-quality embryos. With SET, the chance of twins is around 1-2%, depending on whether the embryo splits (identical twins).\n\nThe exact probability can vary based on factors like the woman\u2019s age, embryo quality, and clinic protocols. Advances in IVF technology, such as improved embryo selection methods and cryopreservation, have allowed clinics to reduce multiple embryo transfers while maintaining pregnancy success rates, thereby decreasing the odds of multiples.",
